{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491351"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:43:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:43:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"919"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/919"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.01,0.22,0.07,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"919"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67937"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/919"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"919"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53402"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"649"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8753"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6016"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7417"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67937"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 35-year-old man presents with a two day history of lower abdominal pain. A diagnosis of appendicitis is made and at laparoscopy a perforated appendix is identified, with surrounding peritoneal soiling. An appendicectomy and washout is performed. The patient is given a short course of antibiotics, recovers well and goes home four days after the procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe attends for review one week later and reports that for the last two days he has had intermittent fevers and episodes of sweating. His bowels did not work for the first three days after getting home, but he is now passing mucous-stained soft stool.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C. difficile colitis","Viral gastroenteritis","Resolving paralytic ileus","Staphylococcal enteritis","Pelvic abscess"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient probably has a \u003Cstrong\u003Epelvic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E. This is in keeping with the presentation of fever, sweats and mucous stained stools. Furthermore, the perforated appendix with peritoneal soiling increases the risk of a pelvic abscess forming. The risk of pelvic abscess formation complicating appendicitis varies between 3 - 25% and is likely to occur more often when there has been perforation and peritoneal soiling. Given this clinical picture, an abdominal CT scan is the most appropriate single imaging test to establish or exclude the diagnosis and should be undertaken. If present, pelvic abscesses can be treated with antibiotics or surgically drained and the choice will often depend on the size of the abscess and the well-being of the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC. difficile colitis\u003C/strong\u003E is seen after a course of antibiotics as the normal gut flora has been disrupted. This however tends to present with profuse watery diarrhoea rather than mucous stained stools.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResolving paralytic ileus\u003C/strong\u003E is common after GI surgery, and the patient likely had post-operative ileus for the few days. This would present as abdominal distension, diffuse abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting inability to pass flatus and intolerance of oral intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral gastroenteritis\u003C/strong\u003E, commonly caused by rotavirus or norovirus, includes symptoms like nausea, vomiting and diarrhoea. Outbreaks are common in group settings such as nursing homes, childcares, schools and hospital. \u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcal enteritis \u003C/strong\u003Epresents with nausea, vomiting and other signs of GI upset due to eating food contaminated with toxins produced by Staphylococcus aureus bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A well-known complication of appendicectomy is a pelvic abscess, with higher occurences in perforated appendicitis."],"references":["Khaliq K, Nama N, Lopez RA. Pelvic Abscess. [Updated 2022 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.\u00a0Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545292/","Guy S, Wysocki P. Risk factors for intra-abdominal abscess post laparoscopic appendicectomy for gangrenous or perforated appendicitis: A retrospective cohort study.\u00a0Int J Surg Open.\u00a02018;10:47\u201354. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2405857217300931","Gorter, R.R., Meiring, S., van der Lee, J.H. et al. Intervention not always necessary in post-appendectomy abscesses in children; clinical experience in a tertiary surgical centre and an overview of the literature. Eur J Pediatr 175, 1185\u20131191 (2016). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27511046/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53402"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"919"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53402"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T23:38:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T23:38:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"919"}},"conte